When you change a setting in the regular /config folder, those changes usually only apply to the instance (the local game). However, some mods have "Server Configs"—settings that dictate how a specific world works (like starting health, ore spawn rates, or chunk loading rules).

    The Problem: Standard server configs are stored inside the /saves/world_name/serverconfig folder. This makes it impossible to ship those settings in a modpack because your users haven't created a "world" folder yet!

    The Solution: You put those specific .toml files into /defaultconfigs. When a player creates a new world, Forge automatically copies everything from /defaultconfigs into that new world’s serverconfig folder.

How to use it correctly

If you are tweaking a mod and notice the config file isn't in the main /config folder:

    Launch your game and create a temporary world.

    Go to saves/[WorldName]/serverconfig.

    Edit the .toml files there to your liking.

    Copy those edited files into the root /defaultconfigs folder of your PolyMC instance.

Now, every time someone starts a new save with your modpack, they will have your custom balance changes applied automatically.